{{Rastafari}}
'''Nyabinghi''' is the oldest of the [[Mansions of Rastafari]]. These Rastafari are the strictest out of the six or so major groups. They pledge "love to all human beings", and do not believe in violence, because they believe that only [[Jah]] has the right to destroy. They make this pledge because of the power of words, believing that only when all of Jah's children make the pledge together, the oppressors will be destroyed. In addition, they are often [[non-violent]] or follow the [[just war theory]].
== Name == Nyabinghi was a legendary Ugandan/Rwandan tribe queen,<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.suppressedhistories.net/articles/warriors.html|title = Jamaica|date = |accessdate = 8 January 2016|website = Suppressed Histories|publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> who was said to have possessed a Ugandan woman named [[Muhumusa]] in the 19th century. Muhumusa inspired a movement, rebelling against African colonial authorities.{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}} Although she was captured in 1913, alleged possessions by Nyabinghi continued (mostly afflicting women). Bloodline of the true Nyabinghi warriors rightfully settled in the heart of Dzimba dze Mabwe now known as [[Zimbabwe]].{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}}
== Music == The Nyabinghi resistance inspired a number of Jamaican [[Rastafari movement|Rastas]], who incorporated what are known as [[Nyabinghi chants]] (''binghi'') into their celebrations ([[grounation]]s).{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}} The [[Nyabinghi rhythm|rhythm]]s of these chants were an influence on popular [[ska]], [[rocksteady]] and [[reggae]] music. Three kinds of [[Nyabinghi drums|drums]] are used in Nyabinghi music: [[bass drum|bass]], ''[[funde]]'' and ''keteh''. The ''keteh'' plays an [[improvisation|improvised]] [[syncopation]] rooted in [[Asante people|Ashanti]] dance and drumming,<ref>Asante Ivory Trumpet Music in Ghana: Culture Tradition and Sound Barrage By Joseph S. Kaminski</ref> the ''funde'' plays a regular one-two beat and the bass drum strikes loudly on the first beat, and softly on the third (of fourth) beat. [[Count Ossie]] was the first to record nyabinghi and helped to establish and maintain Rasta culture.{{Citation needed|date = January 2016}}
==See also== *[[Ethiopian Orthodox Tewahedo Church]] *[[Pacifism]]
==References== <references/>
==Further reading== * Hopkins, Elizabeth. “The Nyabingi Cult of Southwestern Uganda.” Protest and Power in Black Africa. Ed. Robert I. Rotberg and Ali A. Mazrui. New York: Oxford University Press, 1970. 258-336.
